geology. Drawing on archival research, interviews, and fieldwork at Javanese volcanoes and in scientific observatories, he explores how Indonesian Islam shaped the theory of plate tectonics, how Dutch colonial volcanologists learned to see the earth in new ways from Javanese spiritual traditions, and how new scientific technologies radically recast notions of the human body, distance, and the earth. In this way, Bobbette decenters the significance of Western scientists to expand our understanding of the evolution of planetary thought and rethinks the politics of geological knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGeologyxHistoryy19th centuryzIndonesiazJava. 0aGeologyzIndonesiazJavaxHistoryy19th century. 0aHistorical geologyzIndonesiazJava. 0aReligion and sciencexHistoryy19th centuryzIndonesiazJava. 0aReligion and sciencezIndonesiazJavaxHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027089?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027089/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles